abstract: The Times asked the presidential candidates for their views on codifying Roe v. Wade, over-the-counter abortion pills and other policies.
snippet: The Times asked the presidential candidates for their views on codifying Roe v. Wade, over-the-counter abortion pills and other policies.
lead_paragraph: The New York Times asked the Democratic presidential candidates to complete a survey on abortion and contraception. Following are the full responses we received, unedited except for corrected typos and punctuation.

headline_main: How the 2020 Democrats Responded to an Abortion Survey

abstract: Anxious about the cost of a single-payer health system, more voters now support the idea of a government-run plan that would compete with private insurance.
snippet: Anxious about the cost of a single-payer health system, more voters now support the idea of a government-run plan that would compete with private insurance.
lead_paragraph: CONCORD, N.H. â€” One after another, voters at a recent campaign event here for former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. expressed utter comfort with the centerpiece of his health care platform: an idea once so controversial that Democrats had to drop it from the Affordable Care Act to get the landmark law passed.

headline_main: Debate 5, and a Push for Black Voters: This Week in the 2020 Race

abstract: Michael R. Bloomberg, the former mayor of New York City and expected presidential candidate, is buying ads in more than two dozen states.
snippet: Michael R. Bloomberg, the former mayor of New York City and expected presidential candidate, is buying ads in more than two dozen states.
lead_paragraph: Michael R. Bloomberg, the billionaire former mayor of New York City, spent at least $30 million on Friday for a single week of television ads, a show of financial force that signals his willingness to use his vast personal fortune to reshape the Democratic presidential race.

headline_main: The Likability Trap Is Still a Thing

abstract: Democrats have a road map for victory.
snippet: Democrats have a road map for victory.
lead_paragraph: Election Day, 2020. The polls have just closed. All indications point to a resounding verdict. Historians, loath to make narrative sense of an age without waiting for the vapors of passion to pass, agree on one thing.

lead_paragraph: Paid leave has long been a Democratic cause, one that candidates rallied around at the debate Wednesday night. Now itâ€™s also one for Republicans, whoâ€™ve recently embraced a version of it, with a flurry of new bills and a White House summit next month. The debate revealed minor divisions in the candidatesâ€™ approaches; the bigger differences, though, are between the two parties.

Biden Jr. should not take support from African-Americans for granted.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON â€” Congress gave final approval on Thursday to a stopgap spending bill that would punt the threat of a government shutdown to just before Christmas, setting up a potential clash over federal spending just as the House could be weighing whether to impeach President Trump.
